Best Metrics

For a hurler, the most useful metrics are usually the ones that answer: how fast, how clean, how repeatable, and how well-timed.

Swing speed: very useful. Your current peakGyroMagRadPerSec in strikeMetrics.ts (line 27) is already a good start. In the app, I’d present this as Peak Swing Speed, not gyro magnitude.
Pre-impact speed: also useful. Your current preImpactSpeedProxyMps in strikeMetrics.ts (line 35) is directionally valuable, but I would label it Pre-Impact Speed Index until it is better calibrated.
Impact sharpness: useful. Your peakJerkGPerSec is a good candidate, but player-facing wording should be Impact Sharpness or Strike Crispness, not jerk.
Impact force proxy: useful. peakAccMagG can work as a proxy for how violent the impact was, but I would avoid calling it true force.
Swing timing: very useful for coaching. You already compute strikeDurationMs, preImpactDurationMs, and postImpactDurationMs in strikeMetrics.ts (line 30). These can become Swing Duration, Time Into Impact, and Follow-Through Time.
Consistency: extremely valuable. Show variance across the last 5 or 10 strikes for speed, timing, and impact sharpness. Players usually improve faster from consistency feedback than from raw peak numbers.
What I’d Avoid Calling It

Strength: probably not. IMU data from the hurley is better at measuring explosiveness, speed, and impact quality than actual physical strength.
Energy impact: possible in theory, but not honest yet with the current data alone.
Force: same issue. You can estimate a proxy, but not true impact force without stronger assumptions.
Energy / Better Speed

You can estimate more valuable metrics, but you need extra information.

For tip speed, you need the sensor’s position on the hurley and the effective distance from the rotation center to the striking point. Then you can estimate v = omega * r.
For impact energy, you need at least hurley mass and ideally moment of inertia. Rotational kinetic energy is 0.5 * I * omega^2, so without I it’s mostly guesswork.
For clean strike / sweet-spot quality, you’d want high-frequency vibration features after impact, and ideally labeled examples of clean vs mishit strikes.
For ball outcome metrics like exit speed, carry distance, or strike efficiency, you need external ground truth such as video, radar, or tagged session outcomes.
What Extra Data Would Help Most

Exact sensor placement on the hurley
Hurley length
Hurley mass
Approximate balance point or moment of inertia
Stable orientation calibration of the IMU relative to the hurley
Outcome labels: clean strike, mishit, distance, accuracy, ball speed
Consistent sample rate and good timestamp quality
If you want a practical first version for the iOS app, I’d ship these 5 first:

Peak Swing Speed
Pre-Impact Speed Index
Impact Sharpness
Swing Duration to Impact
Consistency Score
That gives players something understandable and coachable without overclaiming physics. If you want, I can turn this into a proposed metric spec for the iOS app: display name, formula, confidence level, and what extra data each metric needs.